Date: Sat 26 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reno Gazette Journal, Associated Press, Fri 25 Apr 2003 [edited]
<http://www.rgj.com/news/stories/html/2003/04/25/40418.php?sp1=rgj&sp2=News&sp3=Local+News>

USA (Nevada): Norovirus Outbreak at High School Volleyball Tournament
---------------------------------------------------------------------
The number of people who say they got sick last week during a high
school volleyball tournament in Reno has now passed 300, and health
officials say they're still no closer to pinpointing a source of the
outbreak. "There are so many possibilities for transmitting this
highly contagious virus, we may never be able to pinpoint where it
started,"said Bob Sack, director for environmental health services of
the Washoe District Health Department.
Since many of the people who got sick were attending the tournament,
officials said it was possible the norovirus infection was brought in
from another city or even another state. "The source could have come
from almost anywhere at this point, including here," said Tracie
Douglas, spokeswoman for the department's environmental division.
"The only fact we have right now is we have [a confirmed norovirus
infection]." Many of the 2160 players in 360 teams from throughout
the West stayed at the Reno Hilton, and they played in the tournament
that ran Thursday through Sunday at the Reno-Sparks Convention
Center. Health officials have said that the virus could have been
spread by any of a number of sources, including the volleyballs used
in the tournament.
Inspectors have said that people who didn't play in the volleyball
tournament or stay at the Reno Hilton have reported symptoms of
norovirus infection. As the health department's search for a virus
cause goes on, the Reno Hilton continues to sanitize all of its 2000
hotel rooms in an attempt to eliminate possible sources of the
illness.
An outbreak in 1996 at the Reno Hilton, northern Nevada's largest
hotel casino, was attributed to norovirus infection.
