[2]
Date: Wed 30 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters Health, Fri Apr 18 2003 [edited]
<http://www.nature.com/cgi-taf/DynaPage.taf?file=/nm/journal/v9/n5/abs/nm860.html>

Multiple Factors Involved in Resistance to Norovirus Infection
-------------------------------------------------
Scientists are learning more about why some individuals appear to be
resistant to norovirus infection and others are not. "Although
noroviruses are highly infectious, volunteer studies have shown that
some subjects remain uninfected even after challenge with high
doses," Dr. Lisa Lindesmith of the University of North Carolina in
Chapel Hill and colleagues explain in an advance [Apr 14 2003] online
publication of Nature Medicine.
They analyzed saliva samples collected from 77 individuals
participating in 2 norovirus volunteer challenge studies. After
challenge with _Norwalk virus_, 44 percent of the volunteers
developed infections. They identified 2 mechanisms of Norwalk virus
resistance: "Innate genetic resistance mediated by inactive
[alpha(1,2)fucosyltransferase gene] (FUT2) alleles" and "acquired
immunity characterized by rapid Norwalk virus-specific mucosal IgA
production in some [secretor] Se+ volunteers. Both resistance
mechanisms seemed to provide complete protection at every dose level
studied, suggesting that both mechanisms are dose-independent," they
write.
These findings support the theory that a functional FUT2 gene and
positive secretor status are susceptibility markers for Norwalk virus
infection. However, "Of the susceptible population that encoded a
functional FUT2 gene, a portion was resistant to infection," they
note. This suggests to the team that a "memory immune response or
some other unidentified factor also affords protection against
Norwalk virus infection."
The researchers also found, as have others, that norovirus-like
particles bind more efficiently to O and A antigens than to B-antigen
saliva specimens. Supporting a prior study, group-O individuals were
more susceptible to Norwalk virus infection than group A or B
individuals. They conclude that: "Although additional human challenge
studies with other noroviruses are needed, our data suggest that
norovirus vaccines may elicit protective immunity and reduce the
substantial disease burden associated with these viruses."
